        content: `<h4>Why Stakeholders Matter in Strategy</h4><p>Strategy is not developed in isolation. Key stakeholders — board members, funders, community members, staff, and partners — have stakes in your decisions and influence over your success. Engaging them effectively builds buy-in and improves plan quality.</p><h4>The Power-Interest Grid</h4><p>Plot stakeholders on a 2×2 matrix: Power (high/low) on one axis, Interest (high/low) on the other. This produces four groups: Manage Closely (high power, high interest), Keep Satisfied (high power, low interest), Keep Informed (low power, high interest), and Monitor (low power, low interest).</p><h4>Engagement Strategies</h4><p>Each quadrant requires a different engagement approach. High-power, high-interest stakeholders should be active co-designers of strategy. High-power, low-interest stakeholders need regular executive updates. Low-power, high-interest stakeholders make ideal community ambassadors.</p>`,
